<DOC><DOCNO> AP880824-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-88 0052EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-24 0492</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0515</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Grocery prices jumped 1.4 percent in July, thebiggest monthly increase since early 1984, as the drought's effectsreached supermarket checkout counters, the government has reported.   However, there was little evidence of accelerating retail priceinflation elsewhere in the U.S. economy, the Labor Departmentreport indicated Tuesday. Excluding food, overall retail pricesrose just 0.3 percent for the month, slower than the pace of thefirst half of 1987, the department said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, hurtby a drop in demand in the volatile transportation sector, fell asharp 7 percent in July, the biggest setback in four years, thegovernment says.   The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that orders for durablegoods, items expected to last at least three years, fell $8.8billion to a seasonally adjusted $116.6 billion last month asdemand dropped off for ships and tanks, autos and aircraft.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Donald P. Kelly, a near-legendary dealmaker, hasresigned as chairman of Beatrice Co. as the company moves away frommegabuck corporate spinoffs to focus on its main food operations.   Kelly, 66, still will play a role as a director and majorinvestor in Beatrice, the food giant he has pruned relentlesslyover the past two years, a spokeswoman said Tuesday.   Frederick B. Rentschler, Beatrice's president and chiefexecutive officer, will continue to run privately-held Beatrice ona daily basis.</TEXT><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Appeals filed in the days before A.H.Robins Co.'s bankruptcy reorganization was to take effect willdelay payments to many Dalkon Shield claimants, according to anattorney involved in the proceedings.   Three appeals to the plan had been filed as of Tuesday on behalfof several hundred Dalkon Shield claimants.   The deadline for appealing is Thursday, one month after afederal judge entered an order confirming the plan, which includesa $2.5 billion trust fund for women claiming injuries from theDalkon Shield birth control device Robins sold.</TEXT><DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal bankruptcy judge has approved a$145 million credit plan for Revco D.S. Inc., a drugstore chainthat sought protection from its creditors in court last month.   ``We interpret this new credit facility as a strong vote ofconfidence from our senior bank lenders and the court,'' RevcoChairman Boake A. Sells said Tuesday.   Revco filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on July 28,about a month after it failed to make an interest payment on about$700 million in outstanding junk bonds used to finance its 1986$1.5 billion leveraged buyout.</TEXT><DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of the West Coast's largest shipbuilding andtugboat companies emerged from federal bankruptcy protection whenfamily ownership was transferred to employees.   Unimar International Inc., formerly WFI Industries, beganoperations with its 400 employees holding 73 percent of thecompany's stock Tuesday under a reorganization orchestrated by theinvestment banking firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>